                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d586">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/12606: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-12-31T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 31, 1933—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>942. Legation’s 928, December 23, 4 p.m. The following telegram has been received
                    from Amoy: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“December 30, 4 p.m. Referring to my telegram of December 22, 5 p.m. As
                            precautionary measure all Americans at Changchow and <pb facs="0659"
                                n="557" xml:id="pg_557"/> Siokhe have come to Amoy. All
                            communications unreliable and troops being sent northward. General
                            Gaston Wang has returned to Amoy. Local situation remains quiet but
                            tense.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
